prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The goal of our proposal is to identify the counterparts to the SCUBA-2 sources in the CDF-S and to measure their FIR SEDs using observations at 250, 345, and 650 GHz. We use an intermediate resolution of 0.5 arcseconds. This matches the lowest resolution in Band 9, which is essential for reliable relative measurements of the fluxes in the three bands. The SCUBA-2 positional errors are typically less than 5", so all of the objects should lie within the primary beam at all three wavelengths.
Our SCUBA-2 sources have 345 GHz fluxes > 1.5 mJy with most falling in the range of 2-4 mJy. We therefore request an rms sensitivity of 0.2 mJy for the 345 GHz observations. This sensitivity will provide good ~10 sigma detections on single, compact objects. In the case where a source is slightly resolved, or offset from the pointing center (due to SCUBA-2's positional uncertainty), or split into two objects (e.g., multiple sources as in Wang et a. 2011; Karim et al. 2013), we still expect good detections of >5 sigma on all of our targets. The 0.2 mJy rms level will therefore guarantee detections of all the SCUBA-2 sources and unambiguous identifications of their counterparts. For the key 650 GHz sources, we have set the rms flux limits to 6 times the 345 GHz flux limits, or 1.2 mJy. For all but the coldest and/or highest redshift sources, this should ensure a robust 650 GHz detection. We have similarly specified a 250 GHz rms limit of half the 345 GHz flux, or 0.1 mJy, which should robustly detect the objects at this frequency.
We do not request special calibrations.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose 250, 345, and 650 GHz observations of 84 345 GHz selected galaxies found in our SCUBA-2 survey of the CDF-S. These submillimeter galaxies (SMGs) lie in the central (5.5 arcmin radius) region and stretch down to a 345 GHz flux of 1.5 mJy. This is the first survey to identify a large number of SMGs in the deepest portions of the (soon to be) 7~Ms Chandra and 3~Ms XMM-Newton X-ray images, providing a unique opportunity to compare star formation and AGN contributions to the FIR light of SMGs. Our primary goal is to use our proposed ALMA data in combination with existing data from the Herschel PEP, GOODS, and HERMES surveys to determine FIR spectral energy distributions (SEDs) and bolometric luminosities for the SCUBA-2 SMGs. We will compare the SEDs of the SMGs that contain X-ray AGNs with those that do not and to local Herschel samples, including our Swift BAT ultrahard X-ray AGN sample, where full spatial information is available, to determine the bolometric luminosities (or at least upper limits) that arise from the AGN rather than from star formation.
